<h1>From Robert Hanson Harrison</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">Sir</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">Aprill 5th 1770</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>I am of Opinion that by the Common Law, you cannot divert the natural course of the Run by cutting of a Race through your own Land; It being stated by Mr Washington that thereby J. Barry would be deprived of Water Necessary for his Cattle &amp;c.as on the Authorities1 Bar Abridgement 45.54. Carth. 117. Com. 69. 5 Mod. &amp;c.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0001-ptr">1</a></p>
<p>I also am of opinion that was a Jury by an order of Court founded on a petition preferred by you, agreable to the Directions of the Act of Assembly made in 1748 ch. 26 (Vid. the Act) to report that Introducing a Race thro. your Land, would deprive J. Barry or the person Intitled to the Land from Necessary water, that the Court would Reject your petition; and should they not do It, that Barry might maintain an Action upon his
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-08-02-pb-0326">[326]</span>
Case against you for any Damage or Injury Sustained by means of your diverting of his water; and that for every new Injury which would probably happen once every year, he might maintain a new action<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0002-ptr">2</a>I must therefore Advise you to obtain his consent by an Instrument of Writing for that purposeIf you should, you will still be Subject to the same Inconvenience from the Heir at Law or person Intitled to The Land after Barrys death unless you can procure his or her consent then or now, If of full age, as no Agreement of Barry can bind longer than his life he being Tenant by the Curtesy only. I am Sir Yr Most Obedt H. Servt</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">Rob. H: Harrison</p>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0219-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Autograph Letter Signed: a letter in the handwriting of, and signed by, the author ]">ALS</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For GWs dealings with John Barry, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-08-02-0211&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-08-02-0211-fn-0001#GEWN-02-08-02-0211-fn-0001" class="document">George William Fairfax to GW, 12 Mar. 1770, n.1</a>. The legal authorities that Harrison is citing probably are: <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Bar Reports</span>; Thomas Carthews <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Reports of Cases adjudged in the Court of Kings Bench</span>, Sir William Blackstones <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Commentaries on the Laws of England</span>, and William Styles <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">Narrationes Modernae, or Modern Reports</span> (164655).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-08-02-0219-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>Harrison is referring to An Act concerning Water Mills, passed in the October 1748 session of the general assembly (6 <span class="ref-st" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ William Waller Hening, ed. &lt;i&gt;The Statutes at Large; Being a Collection of All the Laws of Virginia, from the First Session of the Legislature, in the Year 1619&lt;/i&gt;. 13 vols. 181923. Reprint. Charlottesville, Va., 1969. ]">Hening</span> 5560).</p>

</div>
